ls a pen setter!
- Ah! No! lt ain't so!

51
00:04:40,008 --> 00:04:49,608
Let me! ...Twenty six!...
A pen wiper.

52
00:05:30,008 --> 00:05:31,208
Something you want, little girl?

53
00:05:31,408 --> 00:05:34,608
l'm merely looking, thank you.
l have a right. l have money.

54
00:05:38,808 --> 00:05:42,608
Step on a crack...
break your mother's back...

55
00:05:43,808 --> 00:05:45,408
Here she comes, Jesus!

56
00:05:57,008 --> 00:05:59,208
Neeley! Neeley, we gotta go home!

57
00:05:59,408 --> 00:06:00,408
Beat it!

58
00:06:00,608 --> 00:06:04,208
Mama said.
- Mama said.

59
00:06:05,608 --> 00:06:06,408
l'll beat you!

60
00:06:06,608 --> 00:06:07,608
Oh, no you won't!

61
00:06:08,008 --> 00:06:12,008
Heaven's sake! ls it that late
already?

62
00:06:12,008 --> 00:06:16,008
Well, l guess l 'll just let these
stairs go'til later.

63
00:06:16,008 --> 00:06:16,808
Four cents, Mom!

64
00:06:17,008 --> 00:06:19,008
Well, thas pretty good. Dump the
bucket, Keeley.

65
00:06:19,208 --> 00:06:19,608
Mama, can l...

66
00:06:19,808 --> 00:06:21,408
No. Dump the bucket and bring it...

67
00:06:21,608 --> 00:06:25,208
Today's the day for the insurance
collector and l sure don't want him

68
00:06:25,208 --> 00:06:27,408
to catch me looking like this.

69
00:06:27,608 --> 00:06:28,208
Hot, ain't it?

70
00:06:28,608 --> 00:06:31,008
Yeah. But Christmas will be here
before you know it.

71
00:06:31,008 --> 00:06:32,808
Got enough troubles without worrying
about that.

72
00:06:33,008 --> 00:06:34,608
How's your sister today, Henry?

73
00:06:34,808 --> 00:06:35,408
Poorly, thank you.

74
00:06:42,608 --> 00:06:43,808
Well, hello, Flossie dear.

75
00:06:44,808 --> 00:06:47,008
Hello, Mrs. Nolan, don't you notice
something?

76
00:06:47,208 --> 00:06:49,208
well, you look like you was feeling
better, much better,

77
00:06:49,408 --> 00:06:50,208
don't she Francie?

78
00:06:50,608 --> 00:06:52,608
No, l don't! l don't!

79
00:06:56,808 --> 00:06:58,608
Heat up the coffee while
l fix supper.

80
00:07:00,208 --> 00:07:03,208
Right there.

81
00:07:16,408 --> 00:07:17,208
Mom!

82
00:07:17,208 --> 00:07:18,408
Yes, Neeley?

83
00:07:18,608 --> 00:07:21,008
Mom, if there was a rule about
something,

84
00:07:21,208 --> 00:07:24,208
that doesn't mean you couldn't do
something else once in a while...

85
00:07:24,208 --> 00:07:27,208
Neeley, you cannot have any of those
pennies to buy an ice cream cone.

86
00:07:27,408 --> 00:07:30,408
They go in the bank the same as
usual. Bring them in here, Neeley.

87
00:07:30,608 --> 00:07:34,808
Half of everything we get goes into
that bank.

88
00:07:34,808 --> 00:07:36,008
Thas the way it is and thas the
way is going to be.

89
00:07:36,008 --> 00:07:37,408
Now put them in there.

90
00:07:37,608 --> 00:07:40,608
Gosh, l bet we got about a hundred
dollars in that old bank by now.

91
00:07:40,608 --> 00:07:42,408
Nine's more like it.

92
00:07:44,408 --> 00:07:46,208
Mama! Mama! They're cutting the tree.

93
00:07:51,008 --> 00:07:52,808
Oh, thas too bad.

94
00:07:53,608 --> 00:07:56,208
That was kind of pretty there with
the bird sitting in it sometimes.

95
00:07:56,408 --> 00:07:58,008
Papa loved that tree.

96
00:07:58,208 --> 00:08:01,008
Aw, quit mooning over it. lt got in
the way of the washing.

97
00:08:01,208 --> 00:08:03,208
Tree ain't gonna put no pennies in
the bank.

98
00:08:04,208 --> 00:08:10,208
Mr. Barker. Get out the good cup
and saucer and give it a wipe.

99
00:08:10,208 --> 00:08:11,008
And Francie,

100
00:08:11,208 --> 00:08:13,608
you can stay in the room if you want
to while Mr. Barker is here.

101
00:08:15,608 --> 00:08:17,208
How do you do, Mr. Barker?

102
00:08:17,408 --> 00:08:18,208
How do you do, Francie?

103
00:08:18,408 --> 00:08:20,808
Mommy is temporarily detained but
will join you directly.

104
00:08:20,808 --> 00:08:22,408
Hello, Neeley.
- Hello.

105
00:08:22,608 --> 00:08:24,408
l might fancy you get manners right
out of the book.

106
00:08:24,408 --> 00:08:27,608
And company or no company,
Mrs. Nolan always looks the lady.

107
00:08:27,808 --> 00:08:29,808
You should see some of my people.

108
00:08:30,008 --> 00:08:32,008
Even ladies with husbands that work
steady.

109
00:08:32,208 --> 00:08:35,008
Won't you go. into the parlor and
have a cup of coffee?

110
00:08:35,208 --> 00:08:37,608
That l will. And your hospitality is
very kind, Mrs. Nolan.

111
00:08:38,408 --> 00:08:40,608
Well, old man Gentry is off to jail
again.

112
00:08:40,808 --> 00:08:42,008
Oh, thas too bad.

113
00:08:42,208 --> 00:08:44,008
But she's keeping up his insurance,
just the same.

114
00:08:44,208 --> 00:08:47,608
And here's ours. Ten cents for me,
ten cents for Mr. Nolan,

115
00:08:47,608 --> 00:08:49,208
a nickel for each of the
children.

116
00:08:49,408 --> 00:08:50,608
And you'll never regret it, Mrs.
Nolan.

117
00:08:50,808 --> 00:08:53,408
A fine funeral for every member of
the family, heaven forbid.

118
00:08:53,608 --> 00:08:55,808
And now your weekly receipts,
Mrs. Nolan.

119
00:08:56,008 --> 00:08:59,008
Now, there's one party, not very far
from here, l wouldn't like to say who

120
00:08:59,208 --> 00:09:00,608
that didn't get any receipts
this week.

121
00:09:01,408 --> 00:09:04,208
And naming no names, l will say that
is a family that the angel of

122
00:09:04,408 --> 00:09:07,008
death has marked on his invitation
list, heaven forbid.

123
00:09:07,208 --> 00:09:09,208
Henny says his sister's got one foot
in the grave.

124
00:09:09,408 --> 00:09:11,008
Neeley!

125
00:09:11,208 --> 00:09:13,808
lll mean problems for you, most
likely. And thank you, Francie.

126
00:09:14,008 --> 00:09:15,008
Well, thas what people get,

127
00:09:15,208 --> 00:09:18,408
wasting good money to give her
dresses instead of insurance.

128
00:09:18,608 --> 00:09:20,408
Dresses thall last longer than she
will.

129
00:09:20,408 --> 00:09:22,808
All depends on what folks thinks is
important.

130
00:09:23,008 --> 00:09:25,008
But Papa says that...
- Thas right, Mr. Barker,

131
00:09:25,208 --> 00:09:27,208
it all depends on what folks
thinks is important.

132
00:09:28,208 --> 00:09:31,408
Oh, and how is Mr. Nolan? ls he
working or not working?

133
00:09:31,608 --> 00:09:34,608
Some tell me one thing, some another.
Of course, l don't listen.

134
00:09:35,208 --> 00:09:37,408
Mr. Nolan being a singing waiter,
Mr. Barker,

135
00:09:37,608 --> 00:09:39,808
and what you might call an
artist, his work don't come steady

136
00:09:39,808 --> 00:09:40,808
like other people.

137
00:09:41,008 --> 00:09:43,008
But l'm sure you'll remember when
you talk to folks

138
00:09:43,208 --> 00:09:45,808
that the Nolans have always paid
their insurance on the dot.

139
00:09:46,008 --> 00:09:47,808
Oh, you surely don't think l go
around spreading gossip

140
00:09:48,008 --> 00:09:49,408
about my clients, Mrs. Nolan

141
00:09:49,608 --> 00:09:52,208
Oh, sure not. And how's my mother,
Mr. Barker?

142
00:09:52,408 --> 00:09:54,808
ln the prime, Mrs. Nolan,
as fine as can be.

143
00:09:55,008 --> 00:09:56,608
And she says to tell you she'll be
over...

144
00:09:56,808 --> 00:09:59,608
oh, over tonight same as usual.

145
00:10:00,408 --> 00:10:04,208
And, l trust you're pleased with the
news about your sister?

146
00:10:04,208 --> 00:10:07,008
Well, just what news do you mean, Mr.
Barker?

147
00:10:07,208 --> 00:10:09,808
Oh, well she must be saving it to
surprise with tonight

148
00:10:10,008 --> 00:10:11,408
when the family's all here together.

149
00:10:11,608 --> 00:10:14,208
l'd take it kindly if you told me
what you mean.

150
00:10:14,208 --> 00:10:18,208
Well, l trot around, same as usual,
to collect her weekly dime

151
00:10:18,208 --> 00:10:19,408
and what do you think happens?

152
00:10:19,608 --> 00:10:22,008
Sell, sir, she gives me two dimes.

153
00:10:22,008 --> 00:10:23,808
Yes, sir, she's done it again.

154
00:10:24,208 --> 00:10:26,608
She's got herself a brand new
husband.

155
00:10:26,608 --> 00:10:27,808
Oh, no.

156
00:10:28,008 --> 00:10:30,008
Well, now, l suppose you mean about
her still being married.

157
00:10:30,208 --> 00:10:32,808
l don't mind saying, l had the same
thought myself.

158
00:10:32,808 --> 00:10:34,408
But, l'm sure it must be all right.

159
00:10:34,408 --> 00:10:36,408
She must have made some arrangement.

160
00:10:36,408 --> 00:10:39,208
l'm quite sure she did, Mr. Barker.
l'm sure that anything...

161
00:10:39,408 --> 00:10:40,608
Does she call this one Bill too?

162
00:10:40,808 --> 00:10:43,408
You children run along now and do
the marketing.

163
00:10:43,608 --> 00:10:44,608
Go on, take some money
from the cup...

164
00:10:45,008 --> 00:10:46,008
Oh, but Mom, l want to hear about...

165
00:10:46,208 --> 00:10:47,808
Take the money from the cup and get
a five cent soup bone off of Haslin.

166
00:10:48,008 --> 00:10:49,808
Don't get the chopped meat off him,
though.

167
00:10:50,008 --> 00:10:52,608
He grinds it behind closed doors,
and heaven only knows.

168
00:10:52,608 --> 00:10:53,808
Go to Werner's for the meat.

169
00:10:54,008 --> 00:10:56,408
Ask for round steak, chopped,
ten cents worth.

170
00:10:56,408 --> 00:10:58,408
And don't let him give it to you off
the plate.

171
00:10:58,408 --> 00:10:59,608
And ask him to chop it in.

172
00:10:59,808 --> 00:11:04,008
And then just at the last ask for a
piece of suet to fry it with.

173
00:11:04,208 --> 00:11:05,808
But he won't always do that, Mama.

174
00:11:05,808 --> 00:11:08,008
Tell him your Mama said.
And then go for the bread.

175
00:11:08,208 --> 00:11:09,408
ls Saturday, Mama, and...

176
00:11:09,408 --> 00:11:11,808
All right, ask for a nice pie,
not too crushed. Now, go on.

177
00:11:12,008 --> 00:11:14,008
But, Mama, we know Aunt
Sissy's been married before!

178
00:11:14,208 --> 00:11:16,208
Thas not...
- Sure. l can remember two Uncle Bills.

179
00:11:16,408 --> 00:11:17,608
Thas nothing for you to talk about.

180
00:11:17,808 --> 00:11:19,408
Now run along now and get things
done.

181
00:11:25,008 --> 00:11:26,408
You got no right, Mr. Barker,

182
00:11:26,608 --> 00:11:28,008
to be carrying tales about
my sister as though.

183
00:11:28,208 --> 00:11:29,608
there were something wrong.

184
00:11:30,008 --> 00:11:34,208
She may be funny some ways, but she
wouldn't do nothing wrong.

185
00:11:34,208 --> 00:11:36,408
So, l'd like it if you didn't talk
to people like it was.

186
00:11:36,608 --> 00:11:40,008
Strike nee dead if l'd ever think of
mentioning it to anyone but you...

187
00:11:40,208 --> 00:11:41,408
Yeah, sure, l know.

188
00:11:42,608 --> 00:11:45,808
Well, you might as well go on now
and tell me what you do know.

189
00:11:46,008 --> 00:11:48,808
No point in my being the only one
that don't hear it.

190
00:11:49,408 --> 00:11:50,808
Well...

191
00:11:50,808 --> 00:11:52,208
Ten cents worth of round steak, do
you want it ground?

192
00:11:52,408 --> 00:11:54,008
No, thank you.
- You sure?

193
00:11:54,208 --> 00:11:56,808
lt wasn't twenty minutes ago l
ground that whole plate full fresh.

194
00:11:56,808 --> 00:11:58,008
No, thank you.

195
00:12:05,808 --> 00:12:08,208
Oh, l forgot, now. My Mama wants it
ground.

196
00:12:08,408 --> 00:12:11,008
You don't tell me.

197
00:12:12,208 --> 00:12:13,808
And she said to chop that in with it.

198
00:12:14,008 --> 00:12:16,008
She did?

199
00:12:23,208 --> 00:12:25,408
And a piece of suet to fry it with
Mama said.

200
00:12:26,008 --> 00:12:28,608
Sweet jumping chrystophers.

201
00:12:37,608 --> 00:12:40,208
You know? Mama thinks we don't know
anything.

202
00:12:40,408 --> 00:12:42,608
Yeah, she acts like we were kids or
something.

203
00:12:42,808 --> 00:12:45,008
l bet she has a fight with Aunt
Sissy tonight.

204
00:12:45,208 --> 00:12:48,208
ls got something to do with men
liking Aunt Sissy too much.

205
00:12:48,208 --> 00:12:50,608
Well, Papa says we oughta make
everybody like us.

206
00:12:50,808 --> 00:12:52,208
l guess maybe ladies shouldn't.

207
00:12:52,408 --> 00:12:55,208
Maybe Aunt Sissy wouldn't have
changed husbands too much if any of

208
00:12:55,408 --> 00:12:58,008
her babies would have lived.
She's crazy about babies.

209
00:12:58,208 --> 00:13:01,208
Look who's talking about babies.
A lot you know.

210
00:13:01,208 --> 00:13:02,408
l know as much as you do.

211
00:13:02,608 --> 00:13:03,808
You don't know nothing.

212
00:13:04,008 --> 00:13:06,008
You think you're so smart.
Boys make me sick.

213
00:13:06,208 --> 00:13:07,808
Well what do you think girls make
people?

214
00:13:08,008 --> 00:13:08,608
Here she comes!

215
00:13:23,608 --> 00:13:24,608
Six loaves!

216
00:13:24,808 --> 00:13:26,408
And a pie, not too crushed.

217
00:13:29,408 --> 00:13:29,808
Breaïs fine.

218
00:13:30,008 --> 00:13:32,008
l wouldn't be surprised if it wasn't
more than three days old.

219
00:13:32,008 --> 00:13:33,608
ls that all, Mom? Can we go now?

220
00:13:33,808 --> 00:13:34,608
Yes, you're free.

221
00:13:39,808 --> 00:13:40,808
Where's the fire?

222
00:13:41,008 --> 00:13:42,608
There's a scout for the Brooklyns
tomorrow.

223
00:13:42,808 --> 00:13:43,808
They're looking for a catcher.

224
00:13:44,008 --> 00:13:45,208
Where are you going?

225
00:13:45,408 --> 00:13:46,408
Oh, no place much.

226
00:13:46,408 --> 00:13:48,208
Well, don't go dream-walking,
crossing the street.

227
